to talk about coding.

00:01:21.746 --> 00:01:24.956 A:middle
So, our talk today is divided

00:01:24.956 --> 00:01:26.416 A:middle
into two major sections.

00:01:26.476 --> 00:01:27.286 A:middle
The first one, I'm going to

00:01:27.286 --> 00:01:28.686 A:middle
cover, talking about teaching,

00:01:28.816 --> 00:01:29.996 A:middle
and then Elizabeth is going to

00:01:29.996 --> 00:01:31.166 A:middle
talk about designing and

00:01:31.166 --> 00:01:32.416 A:middle
implementing playgrounds.

00:01:33.096 --> 00:01:34.406 A:middle
But, those two sections have

00:01:34.446 --> 00:01:35.946 A:middle
three main pillars in them.

00:01:35.946 --> 00:01:38.876 A:middle
Goal, passion, and audience.

00:01:39.686 --> 00:01:41.606 A:middle
So, let's get started with

00:01:41.606 --> 00:01:43.586 A:middle
teaching, and specifically about

00:01:43.586 --> 00:01:44.236 A:middle
the goal.

00:01:44.606 --> 00:01:46.636 A:middle
Now, as a teacher, you of course

00:01:46.636 --> 00:01:47.586 A:middle
have to have a goal.

00:01:47.586 --> 00:01:48.996 A:middle
What information is it that you

00:01:48.996 --> 00:01:50.616 A:middle
want to impart to your learners.

00:01:51.266 --> 00:01:52.916 A:middle
But, equally important, is your

00:01:52.916 --> 00:01:53.836 A:middle
learner's goal.

00:01:54.206 --> 00:01:55.496 A:middle
What is it that your learner is

00:01:55.496 --> 00:01:56.446 A:middle
trying to get out of that

00:01:56.446 --> 00:01:56.946 A:middle
content?

00:01:57.276 --> 00:02:00.116 A:middle
They need their goal to be front

00:01:57.276 --> 00:02:00.116 A:middle
They need their goal to be front

00:02:00.116 --> 00:02:01.766 A:middle
and center of the content so

00:02:01.766 --> 00:02:02.996 A:middle
that they stay motivated,

00:02:03.366 --> 00:02:04.276 A:middle
because while learning to

00:02:04.276 --> 00:02:06.476 A:middle
program is not hard, it does

00:02:06.476 --> 00:02:07.506 A:middle
take hard work.

00:02:08.145 --> 00:02:11.986 A:middle
So, a place where I'm sure many

00:02:11.986 --> 00:02:14.566 A:middle
of us have been with mathematics

00:02:14.566 --> 00:02:17.226 A:middle
is to either love it, or not,

00:02:17.226 --> 00:02:19.296 A:middle
and I'm sure we all have friends

00:02:19.586 --> 00:02:20.116 A:middle
who don't.

00:02:20.516 --> 00:02:22.116 A:middle
As programmers, probably most of

00:02:22.116 --> 00:02:24.446 A:middle
us are into mathematics.

00:02:24.446 --> 00:02:25.706 A:middle
We've at least played with it,

00:02:25.706 --> 00:02:26.846 A:middle
and done some stuff with it.

00:02:27.376 --> 00:02:28.626 A:middle
The people who don't get it

00:02:28.626 --> 00:02:31.296 A:middle
though, are often, or who aren't

00:02:31.296 --> 00:02:33.316 A:middle
excited by mathematics are often

00:02:33.796 --> 00:02:35.316 A:middle
turned off by it, by some

00:02:35.316 --> 00:02:36.556 A:middle
experience where they end up

00:02:36.556 --> 00:02:38.126 A:middle
with this long list of

00:02:38.126 --> 00:02:38.616 A:middle
functions.

00:02:39.056 --> 00:02:42.166 A:middle
Polynomials, trig, exponentials,

00:02:42.166 --> 00:02:43.846 A:middle
logarithms, their inverses.

00:02:44.166 --> 00:02:45.506 A:middle
Solving for "x."

00:02:46.016 --> 00:02:48.176 A:middle
I remember, when I was younger,

00:02:48.336 --> 00:02:50.206 A:middle
and sitting in my geometry class

00:02:50.206 --> 00:02:52.256 A:middle
with my teacher, Mr. Carlin, I

00:02:52.256 --> 00:02:54.246 A:middle
would ask him, probably once a

00:02:54.246 --> 00:02:57.266 A:middle
week, I was a real pest, "When

00:02:57.266 --> 00:02:59.976 A:middle
am I ever going to use this?"

00:03:00.466 --> 00:03:01.566 A:middle
And, he would look at me and

00:03:01.566 --> 00:03:03.606 A:middle
say, "Please stop asking me that

00:03:03.606 --> 00:03:03.996 A:middle
question."

00:03:04.496 --> 00:03:06.286 A:middle
And, eventually, after I've

00:03:06.286 --> 00:03:07.716 A:middle
pestered him enough, he said,

00:03:07.806 --> 00:03:09.506 A:middle
"Look, you're probably never

00:03:09.506 --> 00:03:11.226 A:middle
going to use this, but it's

00:03:11.226 --> 00:03:13.796 A:middle
really cool anyway," and that

00:03:13.796 --> 00:03:15.396 A:middle
sort of flipped a bit in my head

00:03:15.396 --> 00:03:17.276 A:middle
to go from looking at math as

00:03:17.276 --> 00:03:19.476 A:middle
utilitarian, to looking at math

00:03:19.476 --> 00:03:20.926 A:middle
as something that's beautiful

00:03:20.926 --> 00:03:22.546 A:middle
and fun to mess with, like a

00:03:22.546 --> 00:03:24.076 A:middle
puzzle to solve.

00:03:24.406 --> 00:03:26.106 A:middle
And so, that really struck me,

00:03:26.106 --> 00:03:28.346 A:middle
and it turned my direction away

00:03:28.346 --> 00:03:29.766 A:middle
from being frustrated with not

00:03:29.766 --> 00:03:30.796 A:middle
having some practical

00:03:30.796 --> 00:03:32.966 A:middle
application for it, to enjoying

00:03:32.966 --> 00:03:34.496 A:middle
it just to solve puzzles.

00:03:34.496 --> 00:03:36.376 A:middle
Now, of course, little did Mr.

00:03:36.376 --> 00:03:37.326 A:middle
Carlin know, that I would

00:03:37.326 --> 00:03:39.436 A:middle
eventually become a nerd, and

00:03:39.626 --> 00:03:41.106 A:middle
deal with geometry all the time,

00:03:41.106 --> 00:03:42.526 A:middle
so thank you, Mr. Carlin, for

00:03:42.526 --> 00:03:44.156 A:middle
teaching me geometry despite my

00:03:44.156 --> 00:03:44.716 A:middle
resistance.

00:03:45.516 --> 00:03:50.106 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:03:50.606 --> 00:03:51.776 A:middle
So I have a couple of examples

00:03:51.776 --> 00:03:53.396 A:middle
that I use to try to explain

00:03:53.396 --> 00:03:54.746 A:middle
this concept to people, because

00:03:54.746 --> 00:03:56.376 A:middle
I think it's so important that

00:03:56.376 --> 00:03:57.596 A:middle
we think through this, when

00:03:57.596 --> 00:03:58.946 A:middle
we're thinking about teaching.

00:03:59.346 --> 00:04:00.576 A:middle
Now, imagine you're trying to

00:03:59.346 --> 00:04:00.576 A:middle
Now, imagine you're trying to

00:04:00.576 --> 00:04:02.696 A:middle
learn how to do art.

00:04:03.406 --> 00:04:05.786 A:middle
But instead of being artistic,

00:04:05.786 --> 00:04:07.156 A:middle
and spreading paint around a

00:04:07.156 --> 00:04:09.196 A:middle
canvas, instead, you're

00:04:09.696 --> 00:04:12.026 A:middle
encouraged, or forced, to study

00:04:12.406 --> 00:04:14.136 A:middle
the texture of colors, or the

00:04:14.136 --> 00:04:15.976 A:middle
look of the color, or the shape

00:04:15.976 --> 00:04:18.005 A:middle
of the brush, but never able to

00:04:18.005 --> 00:04:18.946 A:middle
apply that paint.

00:04:19.216 --> 00:04:20.726 A:middle
It would be really hard to stay

00:04:20.726 --> 00:04:22.386 A:middle
focused on learning to become an

00:04:22.386 --> 00:04:24.286 A:middle
artist when you can't do art.

00:04:24.616 --> 00:04:26.726 A:middle
People want to create, they want

00:04:26.726 --> 00:04:28.056 A:middle
to build things, or they want to

00:04:28.056 --> 00:04:28.786 A:middle
make things.

00:04:29.286 --> 00:04:30.986 A:middle
And, if you had to study that,

00:04:30.986 --> 00:04:32.226 A:middle
it would be very difficult to

00:04:32.226 --> 00:04:33.416 A:middle
get through it.

00:04:33.416 --> 00:04:34.896 A:middle
So much better to let people,

00:04:34.896 --> 00:04:36.126 A:middle
when they're learning to paint

00:04:36.396 --> 00:04:38.336 A:middle
to make a mess, smear the paint

00:04:38.336 --> 00:04:39.456 A:middle
all over the place without

00:04:39.456 --> 00:04:41.276 A:middle
concern, really, for what it

00:04:41.276 --> 00:04:41.796 A:middle
looks like.

00:04:42.016 --> 00:04:43.396 A:middle
You can worry about that later.

00:04:44.056 --> 00:04:45.186 A:middle
Same thing with music.

00:04:45.186 --> 00:04:46.646 A:middle
Imagine if you had to know what

00:04:46.646 --> 00:04:49.066 A:middle
every dot, every line, every arc

00:04:49.066 --> 00:04:51.206 A:middle
on this diagram meant before you

00:04:51.206 --> 00:04:52.906 A:middle
could pick up a guitar, or start

00:04:52.906 --> 00:04:55.896 A:middle
playing with your piano.

00:04:55.896 --> 00:04:57.166 A:middle
It would be very difficult to

00:04:57.166 --> 00:04:58.026 A:middle
get through all that.

00:04:58.736 --> 00:05:00.606 A:middle
So, I encourage people who are

00:04:58.736 --> 00:05:00.606 A:middle
So, I encourage people who are

00:05:00.606 --> 00:05:02.136 A:middle
thinking about teaching to start

00:05:02.136 --> 00:05:02.946 A:middle
with a question.

00:05:03.446 --> 00:05:05.106 A:middle
That question is what drives the

00:05:05.106 --> 00:05:06.066 A:middle
learner's goal.

00:05:06.396 --> 00:05:08.986 A:middle
From that question, the learner

00:05:08.986 --> 00:05:10.986 A:middle
drives internal motivation to

00:05:10.986 --> 00:05:12.986 A:middle
achieve the hard work of

00:05:12.986 --> 00:05:13.916 A:middle
learning the material you're

00:05:13.916 --> 00:05:15.006 A:middle
trying to get across.

00:05:15.866 --> 00:05:17.356 A:middle
Which brings us next, to the

00:05:17.356 --> 00:05:18.006 A:middle
audience.

00:05:18.646 --> 00:05:20.476 A:middle
It is so important that we as

00:05:20.566 --> 00:05:21.756 A:middle
teachers think through the

00:05:21.756 --> 00:05:23.536 A:middle
audience that we're aiming to

00:05:23.536 --> 00:05:24.006 A:middle
reach.

00:05:24.386 --> 00:05:25.716 A:middle
Are they brand new coders?

00:05:25.716 --> 00:05:27.386 A:middle
Do they understand anything with

00:05:27.386 --> 00:05:27.776 A:middle
coding?

00:05:28.066 --> 00:05:29.406 A:middle
Or, are they moderately

00:05:29.406 --> 00:05:30.526 A:middle
experienced and they're trying

00:05:30.526 --> 00:05:32.096 A:middle
to gain more insight into some

00:05:32.096 --> 00:05:33.376 A:middle
particular piece of material?

00:05:33.816 --> 00:05:34.916 A:middle
You need to know who your

00:05:34.916 --> 00:05:36.676 A:middle
audience is and then make your

00:05:36.676 --> 00:05:38.676 A:middle
content communicate to them.

00:05:40.536 --> 00:05:41.996 A:middle
What I often see happening is

00:05:42.026 --> 00:05:44.796 A:middle
people taking syntax and other

00:05:44.796 --> 00:05:47.056 A:middle
things from a computer science

00:05:47.056 --> 00:05:49.166 A:middle
degree in college and then sort

00:05:49.166 --> 00:05:50.866 A:middle
of moving it down to a level so

00:05:50.866 --> 00:05:52.796 A:middle
younger people can understand

00:05:52.796 --> 00:05:52.926 A:middle
it.

00:05:52.926 --> 00:05:54.516 A:middle
So, you end up with this huge

00:05:54.576 --> 00:05:56.246 A:middle
cloud of concepts that you have

00:05:56.246 --> 00:05:57.976 A:middle
to get down, all these syntax

00:05:57.976 --> 00:05:58.396 A:middle
items.

00:05:58.756 --> 00:06:00.166 A:middle
Now, of course, it's very

00:05:58.756 --> 00:06:00.166 A:middle
Now, of course, it's very

00:06:00.166 --> 00:06:02.006 A:middle
important that you understand

00:06:02.006 --> 00:06:04.516 A:middle
syntax, you can't code without

00:06:04.516 --> 00:06:06.526 A:middle
knowing what syntax is, so in

00:06:06.526 --> 00:06:07.686 A:middle
Learn to Code, the way we

00:06:07.686 --> 00:06:09.416 A:middle
approach that, is that we build

00:06:09.416 --> 00:06:11.016 A:middle
this engaging world with these

00:06:11.016 --> 00:06:12.706 A:middle
great characters and these silly

00:06:12.706 --> 00:06:14.766 A:middle
animations, and beautiful audio

00:06:15.306 --> 00:06:17.766 A:middle
to engage the learner so that

00:06:17.766 --> 00:06:19.046 A:middle
they'll go through the hard work

00:06:19.046 --> 00:06:20.676 A:middle
of learning what a for loop is.

00:06:20.926 --> 00:06:22.276 A:middle
Here's an example of one puzzle

00:06:22.276 --> 00:06:23.646 A:middle
that we have that takes Byte

00:06:23.646 --> 00:06:24.866 A:middle
around the four sides of this

00:06:24.866 --> 00:06:26.246 A:middle
world, picking up gems.

00:06:27.726 --> 00:06:29.036 A:middle
In order to do that, you of

00:06:29.036 --> 00:06:30.336 A:middle
course use a for loop, and we

00:06:30.336 --> 00:06:31.896 A:middle
have that stated at the top of

00:06:31.896 --> 00:06:33.646 A:middle
the page, but that's not the

00:06:33.646 --> 00:06:34.216 A:middle
goal.

00:06:34.216 --> 00:06:35.676 A:middle
The learner's goal is to pick up

00:06:35.726 --> 00:06:37.216 A:middle
these items and to solve the

00:06:37.216 --> 00:06:37.786 A:middle
puzzle.

00:06:37.786 --> 00:06:39.546 A:middle
And so, we use that goal to

00:06:39.546 --> 00:06:41.376 A:middle
drive an internal motivation to

00:06:41.376 --> 00:06:43.266 A:middle
go and learn what a for loop is.

00:06:44.266 --> 00:06:45.626 A:middle
The next step is often to dive

00:06:45.626 --> 00:06:47.596 A:middle
into something like algorithms

00:06:47.596 --> 00:06:48.536 A:middle
and data structures.

00:06:48.886 --> 00:06:52.216 A:middle
I love all these algorithms.

00:06:53.556 --> 00:06:54.716 A:middle
Half of these names, I looked

00:06:54.716 --> 00:06:56.196 A:middle
and thought, Hmm, I wonder what

00:06:56.196 --> 00:06:57.366 A:middle
that is, and I almost got

00:06:57.366 --> 00:06:58.566 A:middle
distracted from prepping my

00:06:58.566 --> 00:06:59.996 A:middle
slides by digging into what is

00:06:59.996 --> 00:07:00.556 A:middle
Soundex.

00:06:59.996 --> 00:07:00.556 A:middle
Soundex.

00:07:00.876 --> 00:07:00.943 A:middle
So--

00:07:01.516 --> 00:07:07.046 A:middle
[ Applause ]

00:07:07.546 --> 00:07:08.786 A:middle
I don't know how many of you

00:07:08.786 --> 00:07:09.876 A:middle
have interacted with younger

00:07:09.876 --> 00:07:12.626 A:middle
people, but I doubt very

00:07:12.626 --> 00:07:14.196 A:middle
seriously-- well, many of you

00:07:14.196 --> 00:07:15.336 A:middle
are much younger than me, I

00:07:15.336 --> 00:07:17.316 A:middle
know, but I'm talking about

00:07:17.316 --> 00:07:19.056 A:middle
young learners in school.

00:07:19.826 --> 00:07:21.006 A:middle
How many of them have come to

00:07:21.006 --> 00:07:22.676 A:middle
you with a bucket of integers

00:07:22.676 --> 00:07:24.116 A:middle
and said, "You know, I really

00:07:24.116 --> 00:07:25.236 A:middle
wish you would help me sort

00:07:25.286 --> 00:07:25.726 A:middle
these."

00:07:27.556 --> 00:07:28.636 A:middle
That's never happened.

00:07:29.056 --> 00:07:30.916 A:middle
No one wants to learn about

00:07:30.916 --> 00:07:32.626 A:middle
sorting, they have a goal and

00:07:32.626 --> 00:07:33.966 A:middle
sorting will help them achieve

00:07:33.966 --> 00:07:35.226 A:middle
that goal, so you want to focus

00:07:35.226 --> 00:07:38.246 A:middle
on the audience's goals and then

00:07:38.246 --> 00:07:39.766 A:middle
help them achieve those goals.

00:07:40.626 --> 00:07:41.936 A:middle
So, again back here to Learn to

00:07:41.936 --> 00:07:43.406 A:middle
Code, when we're talking about

00:07:43.406 --> 00:07:44.576 A:middle
algorithmic learning and

00:07:44.576 --> 00:07:46.326 A:middle
computational thinking, or when

00:07:46.326 --> 00:07:47.726 A:middle
we're thinking about using those

00:07:47.726 --> 00:07:50.516 A:middle
concepts to teach people, we

00:07:50.516 --> 00:07:52.026 A:middle
build this content like this

00:07:52.026 --> 00:07:53.466 A:middle
same simple puzzle that we saw

00:07:53.466 --> 00:07:54.846 A:middle
earlier, that's drawing the

00:07:54.846 --> 00:07:56.536 A:middle
learner in to thinking about

00:07:56.536 --> 00:07:58.286 A:middle
what an algorithm is, without

00:07:58.286 --> 00:07:59.386 A:middle
even using the word.

00:08:00.116 --> 00:08:01.856 A:middle
Then, later when we get close to

00:08:01.856 --> 00:08:04.116 A:middle
the end of Learn to Code 1, we

00:08:04.116 --> 00:08:05.276 A:middle
approach this puzzle.

00:08:06.446 --> 00:08:08.476 A:middle
This puzzle is a challenge page

00:08:08.736 --> 00:08:10.606 A:middle
and says to the learner, Hey, go

00:08:10.606 --> 00:08:11.096 A:middle
nuts.

00:08:11.196 --> 00:08:12.626 A:middle
Solve this in any way that you

00:08:12.626 --> 00:08:14.516 A:middle
want to in the most efficient

00:08:14.516 --> 00:08:16.036 A:middle
way that you see possible.

00:08:16.586 --> 00:08:18.476 A:middle
But, this is after a long time

00:08:18.476 --> 00:08:19.636 A:middle
of solving these puzzles where

00:08:19.636 --> 00:08:21.306 A:middle
they start to understand and

00:08:21.406 --> 00:08:23.046 A:middle
think algorithmically, so they

00:08:23.046 --> 00:08:24.346 A:middle
look at this and think, Oh,

00:08:24.346 --> 00:08:25.686 A:middle
there's two diamonds, or there's

00:08:25.686 --> 00:08:27.716 A:middle
two gems, and there's two things

00:08:27.716 --> 00:08:28.346 A:middle
I need to flip.

00:08:28.346 --> 00:08:31.056 A:middle
